---
/**
 * S-corp hub. The federal mechanism and the reasonable-compensation problem live
 * here because they are identical in every state; the state pages carry what
 * their own state charges the company.
 */
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import EntityCalculator from '../../components/calculators/EntityCalculator.tsx';
import { states, stateList } from '../../data/states';
import { stateSlug } from '../../lib/slug';
import { formatMoney } from '../../lib/tax-engine';
import { entityLevelTax, stateScorpTax, PAYROLL_ADMIN_COST, DEFENSIBLE_SALARY_PCT } from '../../lib/scorp';

// The three groups a reader needs to know they are in before anything else.
const notRecognised = stateList
  .filter(([code]) => stateScorpTax(code)?.recognizesFederalSElection === false)
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, name: s.name, tax: stateScorpTax(code)! }));

const withMinimum = stateList
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, name: s.name, min: stateScorpTax(code)?.minimumAnnualTax ?? null }))
  .filter((e) => e.min !== null)
  .sort((a, b) => (b.min ?? 0) - (a.min ?? 0));

const withRate = stateList
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, name: s.name, rate: stateScorpTax(code)?.entityLevelIncomeTaxRate ?? null }))
  .filter((e) => e.rate !== null)
  .sort((a, b) => (b.rate ?? 0) - (a.rate ?? 0));

const notModelled = stateList
  .map(([code, s]) => ({ code, name: s.name, d: entityLevelTax(code, 100000).disclosures }))
  .filter((e) => e.d.length > 0);
---

<Base
  title="S-corp tax calculator (2026) — is the election worth it in your state?"
  description="Electing S-corp status saves payroll tax, but your state may charge the company for the privilege. What the election is worth in 2026, state by state."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <p class="hero-label">2026 tax year</p>
    <h1>Is an S-corp election worth it?</h1>
    <p class="tagline">The federal saving is the easy part. What your state charges the company decides it.</p>
  </section>

  <p>
    A sole proprietor pays self-employment tax on every dollar of profit. An S-corp owner pays payroll tax
    only on the salary they take, and the rest comes out as a distribution. That is the whole federal
    mechanism, and it is the same in every state.
  </p>
  <p>
    What is not the same is the state layer. Four jurisdictions ignore the federal election entirely and
    tax the company as a C corporation. Eighteen charge a minimum owed even at a loss. Several tax turnover
    or net worth rather than profit. Any of those can outweigh the federal saving, and the general advice
    you will read — "elect once you clear $40,000 of profit" — accounts for none of it.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <strong>Salary is a judgment, not an optimization</strong>
    Less salary means less payroll tax, so the arithmetic always points at the smallest salary you can get
    away with. Compensation has to be reasonable for the work you actually do; too low invites
    reclassification and back payroll tax. Every figure on this site uses {DEFENSIBLE_SALARY_PCT}% of
    profit as salary, and each state page shows the whole 20–60% range so you can see what the trade-off
    costs rather than being handed the riskiest number as an answer.
  </div>

  <p class="section-label">Is it worth it for you?</p>
  <EntityCalculator client:load />

  <h2>States that ignore the federal election</h2>
  <p>Here the election creates a state tax rather than avoiding one:</p>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>State</th><th>What it charges the company instead</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {notRecognised.map((e) => (
        <tr>
          <td><a href={`/s-corp-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(e.name)}/`}>{e.name}</a></td>
          <td>{e.tax.entityLevelIncomeTaxRate
            ? `${(e.tax.entityLevelIncomeTaxRate * 100).toFixed(2).replace(/\.?0+$/, '')}% on the company's income`
            : e.tax.grossReceiptsTax ? 'a tax on turnover, not profit' : 'taxed as a C corporation'}</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>States charging the company a rate on its income</h2>
  <table class="data-table">
    <thead><tr><th>State</th><th>Rate on the company's income</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      {withRate.map((e) => (
        <tr>
          <td><a href={`/s-corp-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(e.name)}/`}>{e.name}</a></td>
          <td>{((e.rate ?? 0) * 100).toFixed(2).replace(/\.?0+$/, '')}%</td>
        </tr>
      ))}
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>States with a minimum owed at zero profit</h2>
  <p>
    These are owed whether the business made money or not, which is what turns a marginal election into a
    losing one for a small company:
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {withMinimum.map((e) => (
      <li><a href={`/s-corp-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(e.name)}/`}>{e.name}</a> — {formatMoney(e.min ?? 0)}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>What these figures do not include</h2>
  <p>
    Some state charges cannot be worked out from net profit. A gross receipts tax needs turnover; a net
    worth tax needs a balance sheet. Rather than leave them out silently and show a number that looks
    complete, each state page lists what applies there. {notModelled.length} states have at least one:
  </p>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {notModelled.map((e) => (
      <li><a href={`/s-corp-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(e.name)}/`}>{e.name}</a> — {e.d.map((x) => x.label.replace(`${e.name} `, '')).join(', ')}</li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>Every state</h2>
  <ul class="link-columns">
    {stateList.map(([, s]) => (
      <li><a href={`/s-corp-tax-calculator/${stateSlug(s.name)}/`}>{s.name}</a></li>
    ))}
  </ul>

  <h2>What every figure on these pages assumes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Single filer, standard deduction, the business as the only income.</li>
    <li>{DEFENSIBLE_SALARY_PCT}% of profit taken as salary.</li>
    <li>{formatMoney(PAYROLL_ADMIN_COST)} a year for payroll and a separate 1120-S return. That is a cost estimate, not a tax figure, and it varies by provider — it is the number most comparisons leave out entirely.</li>
    <li>Comparison is against a sole proprietorship. If you already trade through an LLC, some state fees are owed either way and are not a cost of electing.</li>
    <li>Optional pass-through entity tax elections are excluded throughout. They are a separate SALT-cap question and are elective, not automatic.</li>
  </ul>
</Base>
